["$","div",null,{"className":"mb-16 overflow-hidden rounded-[10px]","children":["$","video",null,{"autoPlay":true,"muted":true,"loop":true,"playsInline":true,"className":"w-full","children":["$","source",null,{"src":"/videos/cnc-machine.mp4","type":"video/mp4"}]}]}],["$","div",null,{"className":"mb-16","children":[["$","h2",null,{"className":"mb-4 text-[20px] font-semibold text-primary","children":"What it is"}],["$","div",null,{"className":"space-y-4 text-[15px] leading-[1.75] text-secondary","children":[["$","p",null,{"children":"A two-axis CNC machine built mostly from scratch: wood frame, purchased linear rails and stepper motors, custom motion control firmware. It moves a pen across paper under software control."}],["$","p",null,{"children":"The mechanical side came together faster than expected. The harder problem was the software. I wrote the motion control code myself, handling stepper sequencing, coordinating both axes smoothly without missed steps or stuttering, and managing pen lift between moves."}],["$","p",null,{"children":"The next step was upgrading it to parse G-code, which would have turned it from a proof of concept into a machine that could trace any vector image. That's still on the list."}]]}]]}],["$","div",null,{"className":"mb-16","children":[["$","h2",null,{"className":"mb-4 text-[20px] font-semibold text-primary","children":"What it showed me"}],["$","div",null,{"className":"text-[15px] leading-[1.75] text-secondary","children":["$","p",null,{"children":"Coordinating two axes in real time is a control problem as much as a mechanical one. Getting smooth, predictable motion out of cheap stepper motors is mostly a software tuning exercise. That instinct toward the control layer is what drew me toward autonomy and robotics: the interesting problems are rarely the structural ones."}]}]]}],["$","div",null,{"className":"border-t border-border pt-8","children":["$","$L2",null,{"href":"/#hardware","className":"text-[13px] font-medium text-accent tra